{"/service/ndnp/az/batch_az_apachetrout_ver01/data/sn85032920/0021110563A/1908050601/0171.xml":{"full_text":"r aob roxm\nWEEKLY JOURNAL-MINBR WBDNNDAY, MAY 0, lMff.\nTHE ARIZONA JOURNAL-MINER\nOldest Paper in Arizona. Established March 9, 1864.\nPublished By\nTHE JOURNAL-MINER PUBLISHING COMPANY\nMember Associated Press.\nPublished Every Morning Except Monday.\nJ. W. MILNES,\nTERMS:\nDaily, per year\nDaily, per month\nWeekly, per year\n9Vtkly, six months\nWaeklr. three months\n0\nPayable la\nThe Journal-Miner will be continued until ordered stopped. Bills are\ntat out regularly, and subscribers are requested to pay the same\npromptly. Subscribers who desire the paper stopped at any time are\nwrgently requested to send notice\nfunitwtajfli\nEntered at the Postoffice, Prcscott,\nEditorial\nAnother Evening Paper Dead.\nWith lt edition of la&t Tuesday, thu l.oi Angeles Evening News tin\nqutslionnbly ono of the lent fill tod nml ulmont unrivalled among coast dilllcs\nIn the dust nml ability of itn editorials, gave up tho journalistic ghost and\nwill ho seen nml read no more. There I u treat lemon to bo leurned in tho\ndsailse of thin afternoon dally, by every in 11 11 or net of men who are contain\npitting the cHtablinhment of uu evening, or even a morning daily in opponl\nlion to a newspaper or newspapers already more thnu covering tho field.\nTbo Dally News in Its make up strongly resembled the Chicago Tiuiri\nHerald of half u dozen years ago before it was merged with tbo Chicugo\nTteeord us tho Chicago Hwcord-Hernld. Typogruphicully thu News was tho\nbest looking paper In Lot Angeles. Its rrportorial staff numbered a score of\nt brightest lights in tun I.os Augelei field of journalism. Its iidws col\nvmm were tho brightest, it had a paid circulation of 23,000, larger than any\n'other evening paper In I.os Angeles ud Its advertising columns had u fairly\neaUhful appearance, but the LoH,AngeleH Dally News is dead and its friends\nre in mourning and Its enemies gloating.\nTho News lasted three years after being cstubllfihed lit a field already\ntfally covered in news line by tho Hxpress with It 'full Associated I'rcss re\nport, without whlcn no new journalistic, enterprise can flourish in competi\ntion with a paper which does have that service, This is uu ago oCitlemand for\nlie bent, nnd the great body of the American readers will not bo satisfied\nwith u dally paper which does not print the best, the most reliable news of\nthe world, Unquestionably the Associated I'rcss is tile greatest iicwh gather\ning Hguney In the world, it Is a well known fact that a certain morning\ndally In ono of the -largest cities 011 thu Pacific Coast has been kept going the\npast flvo years by a younger' but more prosperous rival because the older\npaper possesses a full morning Associated I'recu franchisu which the support\ning puper cannot afford to have pass into tin1 hands of'iuiothor morning daily\nlu tho sauio city which stands really to pay a fortune for it.\nThree evening papers nave been started in tho past in this city and all\nhave succeeded to the Inevitable. This is tin- golden age of the morning\npaper. Men and women like to have Hut news of the'world with their break\nfasti. It in In tho evening that most of the great political, social! lramutiu\nand other events of thu world transpire and it is the morning paper watch\nnerves tho news of thee events fresh with the birth of tho pew day. Tho\nevening paper at best is unreliable, because it must gather ipilckly the limited\namount, of news available, and print it without due investigation.\nTo Kill tor Ham Clover the .louruul-. Miner extends its heartfelt sympathy\nover tho demlsn of his able joiirtiil. No man wields an abler editorial pen\nand Southern California has nail no abler champion of thu Roosevelt doct\nrino of tho square deal. Huch men as Clover do not remain Idle long for\nbrnins it ml ability are ccr in demand in the world uf journalitun.\nTONS OP SWEETNESS.\nThis is mi age of steel, an ago of\ncotton and an age uf various\" other\nsubstances, Including sugar. Thu world's\ndemand for sweetening has more than\ndoubled during the last twelve years.\nThe Itrltlsh Hoard of Trade estimates\nthe output of sugar for ItMliI at 1 ll I 'J,\n710 long tons. -Htatistics of hit I show\nthe production of that year as U.SOO,\n000 tons In asmuoh as the increased\nconsumption, in this country 111 least\ncannot be attrlbuted to decreased prices\nof tho commodity, the greater use of\n(t article may be regarded as one of\ntho social phenotni'ii uf the times.\nThe New York Si, a gives statistics\nwhich Indicate that tin- I'nlted .States\nconsumes about 'JO vr .int of the total\noutput and our per capit.il consumption\nshows large ami steady in. reuse. Our\ndemand for sugar ren lir. 1,000,000\ntons for thorxt time in ts. 1 so I\nit reached 17100,000 ton, and it i to\nday very close to :i,000,iiid ton- ,.,ir.\nThirty years ago the wholesale pnee of\ngranulated sugar was about mm- ,i,H\na poiitul, and the per .capita fmisuinp\ntion in the United Htates was about\nforty pounds a year. At the immediate\ntime tuu price of the commodity is\nsomewhat nboVe the normnl, which may\nbe taken at I'd cents a piuirul, 'and tho\nper capital consumption Is a little above\n80 pounds n year, That is, within a\ngeneration the price bus been cut in\ntwo and the per capla consumption\nhas been doubled.\nClassing the sugar of Hawaii and\nEditor aad Manager.\n$900\n75\n2.50\n1-5\n1.00\nAdvaacc\nto this otnee ana pay amount uue\nAllfl\nAriz., as second-class mail matter\nComrnent\nI'orto Kico, which conic in free of duty,\nas domestic, products, it appears that\nubout (0 per cent of our supply is do\nmestic. Tcn years ugo tho American\nbeet sugar industry was a struggling\nand feeble enterprise. It has now at\ntained some importance, witit promise\nof reaching 11 yield of .V)0,000 tons a\nyear in tho course of the next few\nyears. The Louisiana cane industry\nshows lliicttiatlon In yearly output, but\nthe average yearly production during\nthe last ten years exceeds the average\nof earlier decades, Within ten years\nreceipts from Hawaii have increased\nfrom about 200,000 tons to about .'!7o,\nO11O tons ami receipts from I'orto lllco\nhave increased from less than 10,000\ntons to about 1S0,000 tons. While beet\nsugar rutins nearly one-half of tho\nworld's total sugar production, about\nS.pi per cent of the Amoricnn supply\nflomes from cane.\nOur national Migur bowl now holds\napproximately (1,000,000,000 pounds nnd\nfho contents thereof cost us nut far\nfrom VIOO.OiiO.oiM) a yeur. T.iu size of\nthe bowl and our Individual extraction\nfrom it increase steadily. Wo eat\nmore candy more jellies ami more pre\nserves, and where the cook books of\neaiber days prescribed \"ono cup mo-lasM-n\"\nthe books of today call for\n\"agar. The days of \"eornmeal and mo\nlasses ure of tho past. W'u live In an\nage of wheat Hour and sugar.\nOut a copy of tho Journnl-Mlncr's\nindustrial and Mining edition of 04\nj pnfes btsforo the supply is exhausted.\nPBESCOTT'S OPPORTUNITY.\nAll indications point to an early re\nvival in mining in Vavapai county uml\nthe whole Territory of Arizona. .Since\ntho inception of the financial panic in\nOctober last thousands of men through\nout tue country with capital to invest,\nwith their confidence shaken in In\ndustrials which have been used as a\nmedium for gigantic lleeeirig operations\non the stock exchanges throughout the\ncountry, have been investigating other\nsources of legitimate investment, pur\nticularly mining, and signs are not\nwanting that a large influx of capital\nis only wuiting proper representations\nfrom mining men with properties\nworthy of development. During the\npast week one party of prominent\neastern men passed tiiruugh I'rescott\non their way east after a thorough in\nvestigation of a properly on Copper\nCreek in this county, and announced\nHint they would spend many thousands\nof dollars in development. This is\nbut ono of many instances which have\ncome to light in tho past two weeks\nwhere eastern capita) has Investigated\nand determined to place money in Ari\n7.0 n a mines rather than in the industri\nals wnich have been largely discredited\nby shameful revelations of \"high fin\n11 nee.\"\nAlmost daily reports reach this city\nof new and ricu strikes in gold, silver,\ncopper and lead in properties situated\noyer a wide range of country, but with\nin, easy reach (or profitable exploita\ntion by the merchants of I'rescott. Tht\naction of the .Santa l'e, Pren-ott is\nPhoenix Kailroad In giving hatf faro\nexcursion rates between I'rescott and\nthe new and' rich mining field being\nopened up at Parker, on thu 'Colorado\nriver, is an enticing invitation to Prcs\neott merchants to make tne trip, get\nacquainted with thu people and re\nsources of that section, and win a largo\nportion of the trade which is certain to\ngrow rapidly for some years to come.\nTrue there la fifteen miles difference in\nfavor of Phoenix, and something like\neight cents a hundred pounds hi freight\ncharges, but this is trifling, uml be\ncomes more trifling in connection with\nShipments to intermediate points as\nfreight charges are a matter of mile\nage. Tne railroad is showing com\nmendable friendliness towards Prcscott\nin many ways, particularly in its ex\ncursion rates to the Parker section und\nin meeting the cut of the Kl Paso\nsmelters by a fifty per cent cut in ore\ntariffs between Prcscott and the Texas\nmining city. The action of the rail-\nroad is surely worthy of recognition\nby Prcscott uiorchaiits in an endeavor\nto secure outside business uml in this\nway help thu company as well as them\nselves. As stated above, the signs of the\ntimes are bright with promise of a verv\nearly return to prosperous conditions\nwhich ruled nil over too laud before the\nrevelations in high finance brouuht\ndown upon the heads of the people the\nfinancial panic. A seven hundred mil\nlion dollar wheat crop is in sicht.\nabundant rains in the .Mississippi. Ohio\nand Missouri valleys, und otherwise\nfavorable climatic, conditions have\npractically assured n record brcnUinir\ncorn crop. Tho great railway systems\nof the country aro preparing to resume\ntno gigantic development schemes\nwhich were under full headway two\nyears ago. Tho .Southern Pacific yes\nterday issued orders for reopening the\nimmense railroad shops at Keno. N\nvada 011 May 1 giving every man em\nployment on full time and full pay who\nwas employed before the panic. The\nforty millions In bonds offered by the\nPennsylvania system on Tuesday worn\nsubscribed twenty-five times over, and\nso eager werti American investors to\nbuy tho securities that they sent ugents\nto London to gobble up tho twenty\nmillions offered to thu Hritlshers. Tho\nwuole trend of tho standard stock mar\nket Is upward, for tho leading rail\nways are lower tlmn they have been in\nyears and bargains nro to bo picked\ntip by Investors. Everything points to\nan early return to normnl financial con\nditions, and with tho lessons learned\nIn the meantime by jnen with capital\nregarding Arir.ona mines us fields for\nprofitable investment, a golden oppor\ntunity for Ari.ona is surely dawning.\nWHAT A STRAW VOTE SHOWS.\nThe editor of .Success recently sub.\nmltted 11 set of current questions to\n12,000 life subscribers to Hint mni'u\nzinc, and received about 10,000 an.\nswers. The opinions came from eiti\nrens of all ages anil of many different\nwalks of life, in every part of too\nUnited Htntes, of all political parties.\nThe questions wero mailed Jnnunry 2.\"!,\nnnd the answers received up to March\n1 have been tabulated and published.\nThe first question was: \"Should tho\ngovernment exercise a stronger control\nover corporations doing an hiterstntu\nbusiness?\" The nfllrmntlvo votes on\nthis question amounted to 0,110 und\ntho negative to 200. Tho second que.\nHon, relating to tho reporting of inter\nstnto business to tho government, was\nanswered in about tho name way, tho\nvote standing 0,101 nycs nnd 2H noes.\n\"Do you believe thut these reform\nshould be curried out, even, if In\nlolngj\ntnis there should be 11 risk of tcmpornr\nily business conditions? This ques\ntion was answered aflirmiitlvcly by\n0,00\" persons, and negatively by 210.\nThe next question was whether thu\nsubscribers would support the Presi\ndent and Congress in carrying out cor\nporation reforms, even If It meant sec\nriflee in the form of money panics and\nrestriction of bank credits. The an\nswer to this was in the aftlrmative by\n0,1. '17 to r.\nThe greatest difference in opinion\nwtis mi the fifth question: \"Do yon\nbelieve in the policy of permanently\nretaining the Philippine Islamist\" The\nayes were .\",21 1 and the noes 11,004.\nThe sixtn question was; \"Would\nyou approve liberal appropriations by\nCongress for the upbuilding of the\nAmerican navy for Hie purpose solely\nof properly defending our present sea\ncoast and island possessions und of in\ncreasing our prestige among uationst\"\nThe answer to this was 8,218 ayes nnd\n1,0S$ noes.\nThe seventh question asked the sub\nscriber whether he upproved the pol\nley of expending vast sums for the de\nvelopment of national resources, such\nus thu Panama Canal, improvement of\nwaterways, irrigation of .arid lands,\netc. The affirmative votes were il,0.0\nand the negative 200.\n\"Do yon, on the whole, approve the\nadministration of President House\nveltl\" was the eighth question. On\nthis side the vote stood: Ayes, 8,0 IS;\nnoes, UCl. The writers ditl not stnto\ntheir political belief, und tho editor\nremarks that ho bail no means of\nknowing the political afllliatious of his\nsubscribers.\nThe ninth question wan: \"Who\nwould be your, first und second choices\nor Hie Presidency during tue next four\nyearsf\" The answers are tubulated\nas follows:\n'ffirst Secoud.\nChoice. Choice\nTheodore Hosevelt \",100 :I2.\"\nWilliam .1. liryan 1178 OO.'i\nWilliam I